In [30]:
# Selecting object (categorical) columns
categorical_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns

# Selecting non-object (numerical) columns
numerical_columns = df.select_dtypes(exclude=['object']).columns

# Imputing missing values with median for numerical columns
for column in numerical_columns:
    df[column] = df[column].fillna(df[column].median())

# Imputing missing values with mode for categorical columns
for column in categorical_columns:
    df[column] = df[column].fillna(df[column].mode().iloc[0])

10.) Are there outliers present in the column age? If yes, treat them with the appropriate method.¶

In [34]:
# Plotting the box-plot of 'age'
sns.boxplot(df['age'])
Out[34]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='age'>
  • Observing the boxplot reveals the presence of outliers in the 'age' column. To address these outliers, we will utilize the Interquartile Range (IQR) method.
In [35]:
# IQR treatment for outliers:

Q1 = df['age'].quantile(0.25)
Q2 = df['age'].quantile(0.5)
Q3 = df['age'].quantile(0.75)

IQR = Q3 - Q1

lower_range = Q1 - (1.5*IQR)
upper_range = Q3 + (1.5*IQR)

df = df.loc[(df['age'] > lower_range) & (df['age'] < upper_range)]
In [36]:
# Plotting boxplot after IQR treatment:
sns.boxplot(df['age'])
Out[36]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='age'>
In [37]:
# Checking the shape of the dataset after handling the outliers.
df.shape
Out[37]:
(180531, 10)

Inference:¶

  • The boxplot visualization of the 'age' column indicates the presence of numerous outliers. To address this, an Interquartile Range (IQR) treatment method is applied, which effectively reduces the impact of outliers.
  • After outlier treatment using the IQR method, the dataset was refined from 192355 to 180531 records. This refinement ensures a more balanced distribution of the 'age' data, making the dataset more reliable and suitable for further analysis, modeling, or visualization tasks.

## Step3: Calculating the Variance explained and the cummulative variance explained
total = sum(eig_vals)

cum_var_exp = np.cumsum(var_exp)
print('Explained Variance: ',var_exp)
print('\n')
print('Cummulative Variance Explained: ',cum_var_exp)

# a. Finding the optimal K Value using elbow plot for K Means clustering.
cluster_errors = []
cluster_range = range(2,15)

for num_clusters in cluster_range:
    cluster = KMeans(num_clusters, random_state=100)
    cluster.fit(pca_df)
    cluster_errors.append(cluster.inertia_)

# Creataing a dataframe of number of clusters and cluster errors.
cluster_df = pd.DataFrame({'num_clusters': cluster_range, 'cluster_errors': cluster_errors})
cluster_df

  • Upon examining the plot, we can see a distinct bend or elbow around the 4th or 5th cluster. After that point, the decrease in inertia becomes less significant as we increase the number of clusters further.
  • Therefore, based on the elbow method and the visualized plot, the optimal K value or the recommended number of clusters would be either 4 or 5.
  • So, we are taking K=5 as the optimal number of clusters for our dataset. The clusters are labeled as 0,1,2,3,4.

  • in this project, we segmented an e-commerce dataset using K-means and agglomerative clustering techniques.

  • Cluster 0 emerged as the most significant group, comprising older individuals with higher weight and size preferences, particularly for specific fit types across different categories. These customers also provided higher ratings.

  • Clusters 1 and 0 received favorable ratings, while Clusters 2 and 3 exhibited preferences for specific fit types within different categories.
  • Customers in Cluster 0 showed the highest level of satisfaction with fitting compared to other clusters.
